		<title>Why I Chose To Be An Israeli Soldier</title>
		<link>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/09/02/why-i-do-what-i-do/</link>
		<comments>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/09/02/why-i-do-what-i-do/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 02 Sep 2011 13:00:47 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>SYPulse</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Headlines]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thesypulse.com/?p=902</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Written By</strong>: Albert Maslaton, Sergeant in the IDF<a href="http://i0.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/slide11.jpg?resize=490%2C367"></a></p> <p>It’s 4 a.m., and I&#8217;m sitting on my top bunk, in the middle of]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Written By</strong>: Albert Maslaton, Sergeant in the IDF<a href="http://i1.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/slide11.jpg?resize=490%2C367"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-915" title="Slide1" alt="" src="http://i1.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/09/slide11.jpg?resize=490%2C367" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000;">It’s 4 a.m., and I&#8217;m sitting on my top bunk, in the middle of the freezing desert, waiting for my next guard duty shift in about an hour. This past week, I&#8217;ve gotten a maximum of 15 hours of sleep overall. I haven&#8217;t taken my boots off for the last five days. After my next eight hours on duty, I’ll get, maybe, if I&#8217;m lucky, a few hours of sleep. Such is the life, not only for me, but for the thousands of soldiers on the front lines of the Israeli army.</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000;"><span id="more-902"></span></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000;">I get it all the time, from my friends back home and the soldiers here on base. Why are you here? You don&#8217;t even have to be here. You could be back at home, working, going out with friends, girlfriends, maybe even going to law school like you planned on when you were young. You had freedom, yet you chose to come here?! The worst of it was from my parents. &#8220;Hey ma, um, I think I just signed on for an extra year to go to sergeant school.&#8221; &#8220;You did WHATT?!&#8221; I&#8217;ve already started to dread the fact that I have to tell her I want to stay even longer to become an officer.</span></p>
<p><span><span style="color: #000000;">I get it. I&#8217;m not some action-junkie G.I. Joe looking to be some decorated hero for the adrenaline rush or whatever. Though honestly speaking, at 22, I&#8217;ve done it all. I&#8217;ve worked and actually made some money while graduating college and getting a degree. I&#8217;ve studied for a year in a yeshiva in Jerusalem. I&#8217;ve traveled  I&#8217;ve had girlfriends and the best group of friends one can ask for. So why am I here, with my breakfasts of one hard boiled egg, twice (maybe) a week showers and darkened eyes from lack of sleep?</span></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000;">I spent this past week sitting in an outpost in the south of Israel. All I saw in every direction were miles of nothingness. Emptiness. Desert. A fence. I started to wonder what I’m doing here, how obsolete the whole area was. Who would want this place? What am I defending? I finally got a leave from my base and visited the neighboring community. Sitting in a café, in full uniform, gun in hand, an old lady came up to me and thanked me. I chuckled and said &#8220;For what? I&#8217;ve been sitting in a guard tower the whole week in the middle of nowhere.&#8221; She told me, ten years ago, before there was a watch presence there, the community was under constant attack, but now that there&#8217;s an outpost there, she can now walk her grandchildren to the playground without fear.</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000;">It hit me right there. The same feeling I got when putting on my uniform for the first time. The same feeling I got when I swore, at the Kotel, in front of the Israeli flag, gun in my right hand, Tanach over my heart, to protect this country and its residents at all costs.  The same feeling I got after completing a 17 hour, 60 kilometer, march in full battle gear to mark the end of training and my being recognized as a combat soldier. It&#8217;s the same feeling I got when I was chosen for extra training, to lead thirteen soldiers into battle as a commander. The reminder that I am here not only for myself but for all of Am Yisrael to have a place to call home. I am here to uphold the traditions of all those who bravely served before me. I am here to honor all those who have fallen for this country. I am part of something so much bigger than myself. And for the first time in my 22 years, I feel like I truly understand my life’s purpose. And the fulfillment from this knowledge is worth more than all of the money or degrees the world can offer.</span></p>
<p><span><span style="color: #000000;">So yeah, maybe I didn&#8217;t follow your normal career path. I didn&#8217;t marry at 21, I&#8217;m not the next rising salesman making six figures and I&#8217;m not in an Ivy League law school. Despite all these &#8220;shortcomings,&#8221; I have to say: I&#8217;ve never felt this accomplished in my life. Gearing up at 2 a.m. for a patrol is not a chore to me; I take it as an honor. To put on this uniform each day is a privilege.</span></span></p>
<p><span><span style="color: #000000;"> I didn&#8217;t do the &#8220;normal&#8221; thing, and there&#8217;s not a chance that I regret it, not even for a second.</span></span></p>
]]></content:encoded>
