		<item>
		<title>The Downfall of Having Hired Help</title>
		<link>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/08/05/are-you-my-mommy/</link>
		<comments>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/08/05/are-you-my-mommy/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 05 Aug 2011 07:22:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>SYPulse</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Headlines]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://sypulse.wordpress.com/?p=94</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://i2.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/are-you-my-mother-article.jpg?resize=175%2C248"></a></p> <p><strong>&#8220;You have had a woman, living in your basement and eating your leftovers for five years. Have you any idea what]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://i0.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/are-you-my-mother-article.jpg?resize=175%2C248"><img class="size-full wp-image-97 aligncenter" title="are you my mother article" src="http://i0.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/are-you-my-mother-article.jpg?resize=175%2C248" alt="" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"><strong>&#8220;You have had a woman, living in your basement and eating your leftovers for five years. Have you any idea what her last name is?&#8221;<br />
</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"><span id="more-94"></span></span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">A cousin of mine is what our community would call a true &#8220;Eshet Chail&#8221;, a woman of valor. She is attractive, she dresses to kill, she cooks like Martha Stewart, and she has 4 beautiful kids. On top of all of this, she still makes a conscious effort to spend time with her friends and celebrate every menial event with them and of course buy them appropriate thoughtful gifts. Now this is a woman who is always on her &#8220;A&#8221; game, and one to truly emulate.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Or is it?</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> One may wonder how it is possible to run a household with the precision of a german engineer while still getting the opportunity to attend spin class for two hours before getting decked to attend yet another wedding in Shaare Zion . Obviously this is all made possible with the help of two dutiful mexican elves named Anna and Loupe . These women run my cousin&#8217;s house like a factory, and leave her schedule free to accomplish other things.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Maids (or Chadames as we address them when we don&#8217;t want them to know we are talking about them) do everything for us. From walking the dog to cooking dinner, they have mastered the tasks that mommy no longer has time for.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> This would all be fine and dandy, however the one task that we define as one of the most important of all is left to them as well. That is the task of raising children.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Many of us have close bonds with our maids and see them as part of the family, but I ask you one question: You have had a woman, living in your basement and eating your leftovers for five years. Have you any idea what her last name is?</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Do you really trust a woman who you barely know to handle your child and teach it the correct way to act and behave when you barely know anything more than the country she came from?</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> The way one raises a child is essential. Things like manners, behavior, and grooming are not just parlor tricks. These are skills that carry you through life and define you as an individual. They should be drilled into a child&#8217;s head from an early age by one who can provide an decent example. To leave this training process to a maid is not like sending a dog to a trainer. It needs careful consideration and thought.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Personally, I was for the most part raised by maids. One issue that this caused in my life is poor organization. I have major issues putting things away or cleaning up after myself because I literally never had to. When I poured myself a glass of orange juice, the Tropicana carton always magically made its way back into the fridge. When I didn&#8217;t like a shirt and left it on the floor it magically made its way back into my closet perfectly starched and ironed. Toys always put away, and messes always cleaned by these mystical elves that made everything spotless once again.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> Getting older and attempting to correct my mistakes is actually a challenge because cleaning up is not second nature to me. I can step into my bedroom on a Sunday night and quiver at the striking similarities between my room and a recent episode of hoarders. This is not where I want to be as an adult, and it is definitely not how I would want my children brought up.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> I don&#8217;t believe that I am a freak occurrence in this over-indulgent lifestyle of ours. I know of children who spoke Spanish before English, or children whose first words were their maid&#8217;s names. These stories may be humorous at first but in reality it shows our pathetic dependence on others to do things we should be doing ourselves.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;"> In short, hired help may simplify our lives with many things, however it is the difficult things in life that are always more rewarding.</span></p>
]]></content:encoded>
