		<item>
		<title>21 Going On 50</title>
		<link>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/08/04/21-a-year-filled-with-possibility/</link>
		<comments>http://sypulse.org/wordpress/2011/08/04/21-a-year-filled-with-possibility/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 04 Aug 2011 23:21:10 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>SYPulse</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Headlines]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://sypulse.wordpress.com/?p=31</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/211.jpg"></a></p> <p>For many, 21 is a rite of passage—a lawful allowance to abuse alcohol to the point of oblivion; an official initiation]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="color:#000000;"><a href="http://sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/211.jpg"><span style="color:#000000;"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-33" title="21" src="http://i2.wp.com/sypulse.files.wordpress.com/2011/08/211.jpg?resize=300%2C136" alt="" data-recalc-dims="1" /></span></a></span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">For many, 21 is a rite of passage—a lawful allowance to abuse alcohol to the point of oblivion; an official initiation into the morphing “early twenties” that many a senior have hoped to return to; a year where undergrad ends and real life smacks you in the face.<span id="more-31"></span> For America, 21 is a vital year in the thirty or forty that comprise of our youth. For a Syrian girl, 21 is the checkpoint in the race to the altar. Wait! Hold on! This is not another lament of a post-teen single—I swear I’m not here to cry pity tears.  I simply want to challenge the undeclared battle against the social clock.  Some perspective:</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">I am sitting on the beach, surrounded by a pre-teen rocking half a million dollars worth of life commitment on one bony finger, and an adolescent sporting a baby bump through her crop top. I am politely enduring another dismal conversation of butcher bill woes and nursing- versus- formula myths.  As the sun slowly erases years away from my already dwindling life span, I gently tap the delicate corners of my eyes in search of premature crows feet. I am, as you may have guessed, 21. And—dare I say it—single.  If I thought graduating high school set off the Get-The-Hell-Out-Of-The-House bells in my mother’s head, boy did I have it coming for me at 21.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">Before you question my sentiment – I can already see the eye roll and hear the “she put all the pressure on herself” crap—let me bring you an example that is possibly a daily occurrence for a girl in my situation.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">Meet older Syrian mother.  Unbearable small talk ensues. Among this is included: “how old are you, honey?” to which I respond with a somewhat defeated smile “twenty one,” which is almost always followed by an effortful “you’re a baby!” and the dimming of a light behind said mother’s pupil, reading: uh-oh. Damaged goods. Gears begin to turn as mother racks her brain for a guy- ANY guy- for this poor, unmarried girl. Half a minute goes by before I am relegated with the questionable name of  a 32 year old quarter- Sephardic realtor from somewhere in the tri-state area who is, obviously, a <em>really good boy. </em>After politely nodding and smiling with the knowledge that as usual—and thankfully, in this scenario—there would be no follow- through, my day has been significantly dampened at the thought that I must find someone soon, as in, <em>this year. </em> I then return home and push aside my grad school application/ delicious fiction novel/ journal/something really important  in order to scour facebook for a suitable marriage prospect.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">Can you say PATHETIC? I can.</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">Now, I must ask- WHEN did it become taboo to grow up?</span></p>
<p><span style="color:#000000;">I look again at the girls that surround me—those who’s “growing up” was marked by the slap of a Cartier on a pre-pubescent wrist.  While I can’t help but covet their freedom from such pressures, I am eternally grateful for having had these vital years to form my identity. (That is not to say an identity is ever static, because I do believe we are forever growing. Nonetheless, the personal development between the ages of 18 and 21, at least in my experience, were exponential and life-altering.) Now, don’t get me wrong- I fully understand that as a Jewish Syrian community, emphasis on building a family is justified in its intentions as preservation of the Jewish race—but, we can all agree that: A. the purpose for marriage is no longer so pure, and B. times are a-changin’ and so should we. That is only to say that equal attention should be paid to the encouragement of education, work, and personal growth. This is so important, because personally, had I gotten married fresh-faced out of high school, I would have undoubtedly been trapped living a life I thought I wanted. I see now how valuable my life experience hitherto has been, and can only imagine grander changes for my future.  More than that, when I acknowledge what has happened in these passed few years, the challenges I’ve faced and overcome, the mistakes I made and learned from, the mini milestones &#8212; I am PROUD of who I’ve become, and am enormously energized to continue pursuing my budding passions. With this revelation and sense of solace, I look to girls older than me—girls with master’s degrees, full-blown careers, over-stamped passports, creative expertise—with admiration and a new zeal for life.  We are the new women of today—independent, driven, innovative, artistic. Women who should be respected, regarded, and appreciated.  And one day, at the right time, WE WILL ALL GET MARRIED. And then I can return my cats to the wild.</span></p>
]]></content:encoded>
