				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;">In its second season running, Allegra Franco Sephardic Women&#8217;s Teachers College, funded by the SCA, is breaking boundaries in Jewish education.</span></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;">The idea is simple: air conditioning, catered lunch, Torah, and women. Sounds cute, right? Wrong.<span id="more-1857"></span></span></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;"> It&#8217;s more than cute.</span></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;"> It&#8217;s revolutionary.</span></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;">As we enter into the fifth week of the program, I observe closely the goings on in the modest blue-walled basement. For the first time in a long time, I witness women of all ages, social stati, and level of observance, put their needlepoints aside and actually open a book and read plain and simple holy text. Day after day I watch as regular every day moms become their own Torah scholars, gleaning fundamental Jewish practices and philosophies from the stories they&#8217;ve learned from childhood. The sight is surreal- women whom you once thought were merely mah johngg masters and pro kibbe stuffers delving into the pages and arguing the use of one verb over another is remarkable. Whether it be humash, navi, Halakha, philosophy, or one of the writings, there is always a lesson to be learned. In the spirit of what is taught at AFSWTC, emphasis is always placed on peshat, and God&#8217;s message to us is understood at face value. In this refreshing new light, class participants are encouraged to read the Tanakh closely, question the incongruities, and search for answers. Slowly but surely, eager students are becoming well versed in Tanakh, recognizing patterns in language and connecting phrases and events throughout the book. Women leave class with a new perspective on the day, and hopefully on their family lives and Jewish identities. In a community where women learning Torah was once not only unheard of, but looked down upon, programs such as this one mark the dawn of a new era. This AFSWTC/SCA program is even more cutting edge by giving its students the tools needed to read and understand Torah on their own, making Torah less of a mysterious, daunting read and more practical and accessible. You can&#8217;t help but feel at home in a place where questions are encouraged, discussion is constant, and the coffee is always hot.</span></div>
<div><span style="color:#000000;"> All classes take place in the basement of the Hathway shul annex (unless otherwise noted). The schedule &#8212; for both men and women &#8212; is available on <a href="http://sephardicalliance.org/" target="_blank"><span style="color:#000000;">Sephardicalliance.org</span></a>.</span></div>
